[EncDescription_data/units/spg/ger/brummbar]
German designers began work on a self-propelled artillery system with the 150-mm sIG. 33 field howitzer as the main armament in 1939. Combat vehicles derived from Pz.Kpfw.I, Pz.Kpfw.II and Pz.Kpw.III tanks were manufactured in small series in 1940-1942. The last of these vehicles, the SturmInfanterieGeschutz 33B or StuIG 33B, was the foretype of a mass-produced self-propelled artillery vehicle derived from the Pz.Kpfw.IV tank. Just like that of its predecessor, the system’s main peculiarity was the replacement of the turret with a spacious cockpit that had a good protection and was covered on the top. The armament of the new system consisted of the dramatically redesigned sIG 33 howitzer, designated 15 cm StuH 43 L/12. Unlike the basic model, the StuH 43 L/12 was put on a ball mount, and the dimensions of the gun and its recoil were dramatically reduced. 
Development of an assault vehicle designated StuG IV mit 15 cm StuH 43 began in October 1942, and first mass-produced samples were made in April 1943. This system was better known as Sturmpanzer IV Brummbar, and also had the designation of Sd.Kfz.166. The vehicles manufactured later on received a different driver cockpit and a 7.92-mm MG-34 machine-gun on a ball mount. A total of 306 systems of this type were manufactured.
The Sturmpanzer Brummbar turned out to be a successful design. It had good armor and powerful armament and was suitable for fighting enemy infantry and fortifications as well as tanks. It was capable of piercing armored plate as thick as 160 mm with a hollow charge shell, which made Brummbar a dangerous adversary for all types of enemy tanks. Among the system’s few disadvantages were a limited ammunition loadout and a somewhat narrow combat section. 

[EncDescription_data/units/spg/ger/elefant]
This is theWehrmacht’s most famous self-propelled antitank system. It is derived from the Tiger tank, designed by the Porsche company. Judging by military memoirs, several thousand Ferdinand self-propelled artillery vehicles were destroyed on the Eastern Front alone. Meanwhile, the Alkett company manufactured only 90 vehicles of this type in 1943. The chassis is borrowed from the VK4501(P) experimental tank. The fully armored cockpit was located in the back of the vehicle. The front section of the vehicle housed the driver and the radio operator, and the power plant was positioned behind them. In late 1943, a bow gun was mounted on the front section of 48 Ferdinand vehicles. A command tower appeared on top of the cockpit. The Ferdinands were baptized by fire in the Battle of Kursk as part of the 653rd and 654th tank destroyer battalions. Each had 45 vehicles. The battalions destroyed a total of 556 Soviet tanks from July to November 1943. 
All Ferdinand vehicles, which had been renamed Elefant by then, were recalled from the Eastern front in late 1943.
After an upgrade, all vehicles were added to the 653rd tank destroyer battalion and fought in Italy. In winter 1945, Elefants took part in the German counterattack in the Ardennes. As many as 28 combat vehicles of this type were still in the inventory in late March.

