[EncDescription_data/units/spg/ger/hummel]
In late 1941, German command decided to develop self-propelled guns, including a self-propelled howitzer, on the basis of the Panzer III chassis. Their main mission was to provide mobile artillery support to other units. The first prototype on the Panzer III chassis, armed with the 105-mm leFH17 Howitzer, emerged in early 1942. It was never commissioned, because the decision was made to switch over to the Panzer IV chassis.
In late July 1942, it was decided to replace the 105-mm howitzer with the more powerful 150-mm sFH 18L/30 howitzer and put the body on the special Geschutzwagen III/IV chassis. The Hummel was supposed to be a temporary model while the chassis was being developed. 
Alkett and Deutsche Eisenwerke companies manufactured the first self-propelled Hummel howitzers in late 1942. Their production lasted until 1944, and 666 such vehicles were made. 
The Hummel’s ammunition loadout amounted to only 18 shells. The howitzer crew was housed in an open-top superstructure and covered from all sides by bolted armored plates. The crew was protected from adverse weather by a canvas top. The design of the Hummel did not provide for installation of a machine-gun, and that is why the crew kept an MG 34 or MG42 machine-gun inside.
On November 4, 1944, the proposal was made to install the 380-mm Wurfgerate gun in the Hummel, but the project was not supported, because the Sturmtiger, which also used this gun, was already in production. In summer 1943, the first 100 Hummel self-propelled howitzers took part in Operation Zitadelle. The Hummel was used on all fronts to support German tank divisions.
Hummel self-propelled systems took part in combat operations until the end of the war and proved themselves successful, especially for a temporary model. 

[EncDescription_data/units/spg/ger/jagdpanther]
Development of a self-propelled gun on the Pz.Kpfw.V Panther chassis began in August 1942, when the experimental tank was still taking tests. The assault tank was supposed to get an 88-mm gun and defensive armament consisting of a 7.92-mm machine-gun. As the project was reviewed several times, full-scale development of the system began only in May 1943, and final specification of the armament was approved only in October. Also that month, the mock-up of the assault gun, which eventually turned into a tank destroyer, was demonstrated to Hitler, and the second prototype was shown in December. 
The final variant of the vehicle, designated Panzerjager fur 8.8cm PaK 43 auf Fgst Panther I and given the index of Sd.Kfz.173, was fitted with the 88-mm Pak 43/2 L/71 gun and the 7.92-mm bow gun on a ball mount identical to the one installed in Pz.Kpfw.V Ausf.A and G. The tank destroyer is better known as Jagdpanzer V Jagdpanther, or simply Jagdpanther. During the mass-production period, which began in January 1944, the Jagdpanther was upgraded nearly every month. The manufactured systems can be divided into three main series. Systems of the first series carried the Pak 43/2 gun with a monolithic barrel, and the gun mantlet was welded to the front armor. Systems of the second series, launched into production in summer 1944, carry the Pak 43/2 gun with a composite barrel, and the gun mantlet bolted to the front armor plate. Systems of the third series, launched into production in late 1944, carry a different muzzle break and an engine plate from Pz.Kpfw.V Ausf.G tanks of later series (with an additional fan). In addition to that, there were a lot of minor changes; for instance, the driver’s observation devices were constantly changing. About 400 Jagdpanthers were made.
The Jagdpanther is justly considered among the best self-propelled antitank artillery systems of World War II. Having the firepower comparable to that of the Ferdinand/Elefant self-propelled artillery vehicle and the Pz.Kpfw.VI Ausf.B Tiger II heavy tank, the Jagdpanther surpassed them in mobility. Moreover, unlike comparable Soviet self-propelled artillery systems, this system had comfortable operational conditions for the crew, which added to its efficiency.

