[EncDescription_data/units/spg/ger/su_85_ger]
Minor quantity of captured SU-85 SPGs was used by german forces in East front during last two years of war.

[EncDescription_data/units/spg/rus/isu_122]
Success of SU-152 design made development of similar SPGs using IS tank hulls (produced in Chelyabinsk) possible. Development of prototype “Object 241” was carried out simultaneously with IS-85. New SPG looked like SU-152 but was taller (KV hull was more deep than IS hull) to accommodate needed equipment and ammo. Ammunition reserve stayed the same – 20 rounds (shell and round itself were separated before loading). “Object 241” and SU-152 had the same gun – 152mm gun-howitzer ML-20S. First prototype was shown to GKO (State Defense Committee) during Summer 1943 and new SPG was designated ISU-152.
Biggest problem was lack of ML-20 gun barrels – Soviet tank factories could not produce enough. But there were plenty of 122mm A-19 guns and ammunition for them, because of that GKO ordered Chelyabinsk design bureau SKB-2 to find a way to install A-19 to ISU-152 hull. It was relatively easy task – A-19 and ML-20 were using the same gun carriage for using in the field, so only ammunition rack was re-designed. Experimental prototype “Object 242” was ready before end of 1943 and new SPG was designated ISU-122. First 35 ISU-152 and ISU-122 SPGs were made in December 1943 along with IS-85 production.

[EncDescription_data/units/spg/rus/isu_122s]
Soviet engineers tried to increase ISU firepower during the war. A-19 cannon, modernized for use in IS-2 tanks, had ‘falling’ breech-mechanism. New D-25S cannon had rate of fire of 2-3 shots per minute (A-19 had ROF of 1.5-2 spm). Soon it was decided to install the new cannon on ISU-122 too, new prototype was called “Object 249”, it had new gun mantle with better horizontal fire angles in addition to new cannon and crew of new SPG were stationed inside more conveniently.
“Object 249” was designated ISU-122-2 or ISU-122S. All three self-propelled guns – ISU-152, ISU-122 and ISU-122S were produced using IS heavy tank chassis for easy production.

[EncDescription_data/units/spg/ger/stuh_42]
Initially StuG III was designed as direct fire support assault gun for infantry and the armament of StuG III Ausf. A-E SPGs – short-barelled 7.5cm Stu.K. 37 L/24 tank gun – was intended for eliminating enemy infantry in trenches, HMG and artillery positions, light pillboxes. But when Blitzkrieg against USSR turned out to be a long and exhaustive war, German high command was forced to revise StuG tactics to combat Soviet T-34 and KV tanks. Starting in March 1942, production of new StuGs with long-barreled guns intended for anti-tank use begun, and almost all early StuGs were rearmed with long-barreled guns before Summer 1943. As a compensation, company Altmaerkische Kettenwerk, GmbH was ordered to produce in 1942 12 SPGs with 10.5cm le F.H.  howitzers made by Rheinmetall-Borsig.
New cannon differed from field howitzer by recoil-dampener, two-chambered muzzle brake and breech mechanism, while barrel and ballistics remained the same. Assault howitzer could be turned in 24° angle horizontally and from -10° to +20° vertically (much lower than optimal for howitzer 45°). Ammunition reserve consisted of 36 rounds (shell and round itself were separated before loading) – Sprenggranaten (HE) и Hohlladungsgranaten (AP). Additional weaponry consisted of MG-34.
First experimental howitzer was installed in StuG III Ausf.E by Alkett before March 1942, and at 2nd October 1942 Albert Shpeer showed it to Hitler and said that 6 Sturmhaubitze of 12 planned are ready. Fuhrer was very pleased with new vehicle. Experimental series was made of early StuG III SPGs, while StuG III Ausf.F/8, which were produced in that time, were not involved in the experiment. Mass production of Sturmhaubitze begun at March 1943.
18 March 1943 new vehicle was officially designated Sturmgeschütz III für 10.5 cm Stu.Haub.42 (Sd.Kfz.142/2), but in August 1944 Generalinspektuer der Panzertroppen called it more shortly – Sturmhaubitze 42 (StuH 42), (SdKfz 142/2). This SPGs were made using StuG III Ausf.F (prototypes), Ausf.F/8 и Ausf.G, almost all changes in StuG III construction were effective for StuH 42 too.
In September 1944 StuH 42 were produced without muzzle brakes (muzzle brakes from le.FH.18 and le.18/40 were planned to be used instead).
In the middle of 1944 StuH 42 received new cast gun mantle Tpfblende, but SPGs with welded mantles were produced in parallel.
StuH 42 SPGs were issued to SPG battalions in motorized divisions and SPG battalions in infantry divisions. Near the end of the war sometimes AT battalions in Panzer divisions had company of StuH 42 instead of Stug III, Germans tried to keep the proportion of 7 StuG III : 3 StuH 42 in a battery.
These assault howitzers saw first-time action in Kursk salient (68 units were deployed). After that, they were used in Africa, Italy and France as well as East front.

[EncDescription_data/units/spg/pol/su_76m_pol]
Polish forces in 1944-1945 (Vojsko Polskoje) were the best armed and numerous USSR allies (Polish units were formed and armed – with Soviet weapons in most cases – in USSR territory). Their  structure was a replica of Soviet forces one and they used many Soviet armored vehicles – IS2, T-34-85, T-34-43, ISU-152, SU-76M and others.

