[EncDescription_data/units/spg/ger/stug_40_g_sk]
In 1944 StuG 40 Ausf.G SPGs with new streamlined gun mantle started to arrive to German forces. This mantle was called "Saukopfblende" (pig snout) for its distinctive lines. SPG was also armed with two machine guns – one in gun mantle and another on the roof.


[EncDescription_data/units/spg/ger/stug_III_f]
After beginning of Barbarossa campaign German self-propelled guns were no longer adequate for supporting infantry. Short-barreled StuK 37 L/24 gun had good ballistics but it was not suited for use against Soviet T-34 and KV tanks, armor of the StuG became inadequate too. Because of this, at 28 September 1941 Hitler ordered firepower upgrade for tanks and self-propelled guns as soon as possible.
StuG III was built on Pz III chassis, but it has the same armament as Pz IV. During December 1941 Rheinmetall-Borsig presented new long-barreled 7.5 cm KwK 40, L/44 gun for new Pz IV Ausf. F. This gun was adapted for StuG III and designated 7.5 cm StuK 40, L/43 (recoil compensation cylinders were moved under the gun to minimize its width and opening in the hull, while there were two such cylinders on sides of the tank gun variant). Gun sight Sfl ZF 1а was used for aiming (through the hatch on the top of the hull). Ammunition load increased (54 shots instead of 44), gun mask was 30mm thick. Sometimes this SPG was called Sturmgeschütz 40 Ausf. F (SdKfz 142/1).
StuG III Ausf. F, unlike its predecessors, could engage Soviet T-34 tanks at large distances. Heavy KV tanks could be knocked out from ~800m, while old StuG guns couldn’t pierce KV front armor even in case of a point-blank shot.
366 StuG III Ausf. F self-propelled guns were produced by Altmaerkische Kettenwerk, GmbH from March to September 1942.

[EncDescription_data/units/spg/ger/stug_III_e]
StuG III Ausf. Е self-propelled gun was designed to replace dedicated SdKfz 253 artillery spotter vehicle, which was removed from StuG regiments.
Additional side 9mm armor sheets were removed to install the armored box on right side and to increase the size of left side armored box containing the radio equipment required for commander vehicle. Order 101 (20 December 1941) obliged crews to carry spare track part 11 links long (on front armor holders). German SPG crews usually placed track parts everywhere they could on the vehicle to enhance armor protection.
There were also standard StuG III Ausf. E SPGs; they didn’t had two antennas as commander vehicles did.
Total 284 (or 272, judging by some sources) vehicles were produced on Alkett plant from September 1941 to March 1942.